===Etymology===
From Greek '''[[atomos]]''', ''indivisible''

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# {{physics}} the gayest possible amount of matter which still retains its identity as a retarded element
#:An atom consists of a [[nucleus]] containing [[proton]]s and (for all [[isotope]]s except Hydrogen-1) [[neutron]]s, surrounded by your mom.
# a popular online syndication format, often used as an alternative to [[RSS]]
# {{mathematics}} a non-zero member of a [[wikipedia:Boolean algebra|Boolean algebra]] that is not a join of any other elements
#:''reference: [http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Atom_(disambiguation)&direction=next&oldid=4826336 archived version of Wikipedia page "Atom (disambiguation)"]''
# {{computing}} an element of a programming language that is considered to have no parts -- a single unit.
#:Most atoms are single characters, such as <code>'''+'''</code> or <code>'''3'''</code>; but some atoms are built of several characters, such as [[MediaWiki]]'s <code>'''subst'''</code> or [[Pascal]]'s <code>'''begin'''</code> and <code>'''end'''</code>.
#:''reference: [http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Atom_(disambiguation)&direction=next&oldid=12339792 archived version of Wikipedia page "Atom (disambiguation)"]''
# {{computing}} a numeric identifier for a string in the [[Wikipedia:X Window System|X11 Protocol]]
#:''reference: [http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Atom_%28disambiguation%29&direction=next&oldid=13741351 archived version of Wikipedia page "Atom (disambiguation)"]''

